{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473659"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:12:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:12:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2684"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2684","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2684"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.8,0.04,0.05,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2684"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78869"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2684","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2684"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2684"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64218"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"148"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3260"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3459"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27029"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34390"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78869"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a fever of eight days duration. Additionally, he was taken to the General Practitioner five days ago for red, irritated eyes, for which the General Practitioner prescribed eye drops with good effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe was previously well, with no diagnosed medical conditions and no regular medications. He attends daycare, with no illnesses going around to the parents\u0027 knowledge. His mother has been giving him regular paracetamol for his fever; however, his temperature has remained elevated, currently at 38.9\u00b0C. He has a mild tachycardia; other vital signs on presentation are within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he is not toxic in appearance but looks a little uncomfortable. He has no increased work of breathing. He has cracked lips, a maculopapular rash over his torso, and swelling over his hands and feet bilaterally, with skin peeling around his nail-beds.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hand, foot and mouth disease","Kawasaki Disease","Stevens-Johnson Syndrome","Scarlet Fever","Measles"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis boy has \u003Cstrong\u003EKawasaki Disease (KD)\u003C/strong\u003E. KD is a vasculitis predominantly affecting medium-sized arteries. This affects children aged 2-11, mostly boys. It is a clinical diagnosis made up of fever for at least five days, and four out of five of the following:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChanges in extremities:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcute: Erythema of palms, soles; edema of hands, feet\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESubacute: Periungual peeling of fingers, toes in weeks 2 and 3\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPolymorphous exanthem\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBilateral bulbar conjunctival injection without exudate\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChanges in lips and oral cavity: erythema, lip cracking, strawberry tongue, diffuse injection of oral and pharyngeal mucosa\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECervical lymphadenopathy (\u0026gt;1.5 cm diameter), usually unilateral\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese features do not have to all be present at the same time. They are included if they have occurred at any stage during the illness. (Nelson Textbook of Paediatrics, 2016)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHand, foot and mouth disease\u003C/strong\u003E usually has small white blisters or an erythematous rash with brown scale.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScarlet fever\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by group A streptococcal infection. It causes a \u0027sandpaper\u0027 rash which typically begins 1-2 days after onset of fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStevens-Johnson syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a skin reaction triggered by drugs, often systemic antibiotics. It does cause the skin peeling described, however usually begins at the trunk and spreads peripherally, sparing the scalp, palms and soles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasles\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by a high fever, cough, coryza, conjunctivitis, and a maculopapular rash that typically starts on the face and spreads downwards. The presence of cracked lips and extremity changes makes measles less likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Kawasaki Disease should be considered in any child with a prolonged fever.","Kawasaki Disease is a vasculitis that primarily affects medium-sized arteries in children.","Prompt recognition and treatment of Kawasaki Disease is crucial to prevent coronary artery aneurysms."],"references":["Morishita KA, Goldman RD. Current Approach to the Evaluation and Management of Incomplete Kawasaki Disease in the Emergency Department. Pediatr Emerg Care. 2020 Nov;36(11):537-541. doi: 10.1097/PEC.0000000000002259. PMID: 33122594. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33122594/","Nelson, W. E., Behrman, R. E., Kliegman, R. M., \u0026 Arvin, A. M. (1996). Nelson textbook of pediatrics. In Nelson textbook of pediatrics (pp. 2200-2200).","Sharma, A., \u0026 Singh, S.. Kawasaki Disease. Pediatric Rheumatology: A Clinical Viewpoint, 451\u2013459. 2016. https://doi.org/10.1007/978-981-10-1750-6_35 Avaiable from: https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-981-10-1750-6_35#citeas"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64218"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2684"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64218"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T10:07:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T10:09:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2684"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78869"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tag